Modelling depression with SHARE data - using survey weights

Lara Lusa and Marianne Huebner

7/12/2021

source("scripts/f_readRShare.r")
load(file="out/DepressionSHAREModel.Rdata")

1 Weights in SHARE data

This document gives some examples on how to use the survey weights with SHARE data, using the study on depression as an example.

In SHARE study the sampling designs differ substantially across participating countries, from simple random sampling to multistage designs.

Both study design weights and calibrated weights are available. Study design weights take into account the selection probabilities, but their usage is discouraged, due to unit non-response and sample attrition at each follow-up.

Calibrated weights are re-weighted design weights that take the unit non-response into account and their use is advocated for inference to the target population.

Both cross-sectional (gv_weights modules) and longitudinal weights (gv_weights_longitudinal modules) are available. The target population for the longitudinal analysis is the population surviving up to the time is considered, to take sample attrition due to mortality into account. The longitudinal weights are provided for paired comparisons of adjacent waves or for the analysis of all available waves and stored in the {gv_weights_longitudinal modules). The modules specific to weights include also variables that indicate the strata (stratum1) and the primary sampling units (psu) (the availability differs depending on the sampling strategy of the region).

In the following we use functions from the survey and srvyr R packages for dealing with weights.

1.1 Study of depression using participants from single waves

Here we limit the attention to participants from single waves, retrieve the cross-sectional weights and merge the weights with the data needed for modelling probability of depression, as described for the analysis of the first interviews.

1.1.1 Retrieving survey weights and joining them with data

The code below retrieves the cross-sectional weights for Wave 5, and joins the data that contain the outcome variable and the covariates used in the regression models.

#retrieval of weights from wave 1
share.data.weights <- f_readRShare(
  datadir = "sharedata",
  waves = 5,
  modules = "gv_weights",
  modules.wX = NULL  ,
  countries = NULL,
  variables.in.modules = NULL,
  keep.module.name.in.vars = FALSE,
  verbose = FALSE
)$df.w



# obtain only data from wave 1 from those used to develop the models that include all waves
share.data.w1 <- filter(share.data$df.w, Wave=="Wave 5")
share.data.w1 <- mutate(share.data.w1, age_int_stand = age_int -50)

# join with variable data
share.data.w1 <- left_join(share.data.weights[,c("mergeid", "dw_w5", "cciw_w5", "subsample", "stratum1", "stratum2", "psu", "ssu")], share.data.w1,  by="mergeid")

# filter out the observations with missing weights
share.data.w1  <- filter(share.data.w1, !is.na(cciw_w5))


#dropping the participants from Israel
share.data.w1  <- filter(share.data.w1, country != "Israel")

#dropping unused levels
share.data.w1 <- droplevels(share.data.w1)

1.1.2 Estimation of weighted prevalence of depression

Here we estimate the weighted proportion of participants with depression by region, using the calibrated weights. We use stratum1 as the stratification variable and psu as the primary sampling unit identifier. For the countries that did not use stratification (stratum1 not specified) we defined a single stratum), for those that did not use clustering (psu not specified) we used a different psu value for each participant. The table below shows the classification of countries based on the sampling design.

# assign weights equal to 1 to all participants in an additional variable to obtain unweighted estimates
share.data.w1$wAll1 <- 1


# setting to missing the strata and psu values that are empty
share.data.w1$stratum1[share.data.w1$stratum1==""] <- NA
share.data.w1$psu[share.data.w1$psu==""] <- NA
# number of missing psu
num.na.psu <- sum(is.na(share.data.w1$psu))
share.data.w1$psu <- as.numeric(share.data.w1$psu)

# using constant values for strata within country, all different values of psu for countries that did not have them in the design
share.data.w1$stratum1[is.na(share.data.w1$stratum1)] <- paste(share.data.w1$country[is.na(share.data.w1$stratum1)], "fake stratum")
share.data.w1$psu[is.na(share.data.w1$psu)] <- c((10^9+1) :  (10^9+num.na.psu))

1.1.3 Regression analysis

Here we show how to fit the weighted logistic regression models with the svyglm function, using the calibrated weights and taking the sampling design into account.

1.1.3.1 Unadjusted models - weighted models and comparsion with unweighted

my.mod <- lm(gender ~ rcs(age_int_stand) ,  
                                             data=share.data.w1[, ], family="binomial",  x=TRUE, y=TRUE)

#save the spline terms in the complete data set for further use
share.data.w1 <- share.data.w1 %>% mutate(age1 = my.mod$x[,2],
                                                                    age2 = my.mod$x[,3],
                                                                    age3 = my.mod$x[,4],
                                                                    age4 = my.mod$x[,5])
    

my.mod <- glm(eurodcat_imp ~ rcs(age_int_stand) + gender + region + 
                       rcs(age_int_stand):region + rcs(age_int_stand):gender + gender:region ,  
                                             data=share.data.w1, family="binomial",  x=TRUE, y=TRUE)


# retrieve the location of knots used and assign them to Knots variable
Knots <- Hmisc::rcspline.eval(x = share.data.w1$age_int_stand, nk = 5, knots.only = TRUE)

#reproduces the spline values for age, expands for each integer value from 50 to 90
age = rcspline.eval(c(50:90)-50, knots=Knots)
age <- cbind.data.frame(age1=c(50:90)-50, age )
dimnames(age)[[2]] <- c("age1", "age2", "age3", "age4")






if(!is.null(my.mod$na.action)){
my.mod2 <- glm(eurodcat_imp ~ age1 + age2 + age3 + age4 + gender + region + 
                      age1:region + age2:region + age3:region + age4:region +  
                       age1:gender + age2:gender + age3:gender + age4:gender +  
                       gender:region ,
                        data=share.data.w1[-my.mod$na.action,], family="binomial",  x=TRUE, y=TRUE)} else {
 my.mod2 <- glm(eurodcat_imp ~ age1 + age2 + age3 + age4 + gender + region + 
                      age1:region + age2:region + age3:region + age4:region +  
                       age1:gender + age2:gender + age3:gender + age4:gender +  
                       gender:region ,
                        data=share.data.w1, family="binomial",  x=TRUE, y=TRUE)
}





#derive the data.frame containing the levels of the covariatee, where the probabilities of depression estimated by the model will be derived
data.grid <- expand.grid(age1=age[,1], gender=levels(share.data.w1$gender), region=levels(share.data.w1$region))

1.1.4 Analysis of the other waves

Also using the other single waves the results between weighted and unweighted analyses were similar.

The most notable difference was observed in Wave 1, where the sample was the smallest. The weighted analysis gave extremely variable estimates (for the estimated probabilities after year 65). We conducted a sensitivity analysis were we removed the participants with largest weights (<1% participants with weighted >20000): the variability was greatly reduced and the results obtained from the two analyses were very similar.

share.data.w1 <- droplevels(share.data.w1)
# assign weights equal to 1 to all participants in an additional variable to obtain unweighted estimates
share.data.w1$wAll1 <- 1


# setting to missing the strata and psu values that are empty
share.data.w1$stratum1[share.data.w1$stratum1==""] <- NA
share.data.w1$psu[share.data.w1$psu==""] <- NA
# number of missing psu
num.na.psu <- sum(is.na(share.data.w1$psu))
share.data.w1$psu <- as.numeric(share.data.w1$psu)

# using constant values for strata within country, all different values of psu for countries that did not have them in the design
share.data.w1$stratum1[is.na(share.data.w1$stratum1)] <- paste(share.data.w1$country[is.na(share.data.w1$stratum1)], "fake stratum")
share.data.w1$psu[is.na(share.data.w1$psu)] <- c((10^9+1) :  (10^9+num.na.psu)) 


# specify the sampling design
dstrat <- survey::svydesign(id=~psu,strata=~stratum1, weights=~ cciw_w6,
data = share.data.w1, nest=TRUE)

# id=psu specifies sampling at primary sampling unit.
# stratum1 is a factor variable for stratum used for sampling, usually geographical units
# share.data.w1 is the data frame with all the data.
# cciw_w6 contains calibrated sampling weights

# remove the participants not used in the analysis - removed because of missing data or exclusion criteria
dstrat <- subset(dstrat, !is.na(eurodcat_imp))

#to take into account the problem related to strata with a single psu
options(survey.lonely.psu="adjust")

f.table <- function(df)
{
  a <- paste0(round(df[,3],2), " (", round(df[,4],2),"-", round(df[,5],2), ") ")
  b <- paste0(round(df[,6],2), " (", round(df[,7],2),"-", round(df[,8],2), ") ")
  cbind.data.frame(df[,1:2], UW = a, WD= b)
}


f.table2 <- function(df)
{
  a <- paste0(" ", round(df[,1],2), " (", round(df[,2],2),"-", round(df[,3],2),    ") ", "; P=", ifelse(df[,4]>0.01, round(df[,4], 2), "<0.01"),  "  ")
  b <- paste0(" ", round(df[,5],2), " (", round(df[,6],2),"-", round(df[,7],2),  ") ",  "; P=", ifelse(df[,8]>0.01, round(df[,4], 2), "<0.01") , "  ")
  df1<-cbind.data.frame(`UW OR` = a, `WD OR`= b)
  dimnames(df1)[[1]] <- dimnames(df)[[1]]
  df1
 }

1.1.6 Sensitivity analysis for wave 1

As we observed big differences between weighted and unweighthed analyses in Wave 1, we remove subjects with large weights and refit the models.

#retrieval of weights from wave 1
share.data.weights <- f_readRShare(
  datadir = "sharedata",
  waves = 1,
  modules = "gv_weights",
  modules.wX = NULL  ,
  countries = NULL,
  variables.in.modules = NULL,
  keep.module.name.in.vars = FALSE,
  verbose = FALSE
)$df.w



# obtain only data from wave 1 from those used to develop the models that include all waves
share.data.w1 <- filter(share.data.first.interview, Wave=="Wave 1")

# join with variable data
share.data.w1 <- left_join(share.data.weights[,c("mergeid", "dw_w1", "cciw_w1", "subsample", "stratum1", "stratum2", "psu", "ssu")], share.data.w1,  by="mergeid")

# filter out the observations with missing weights
share.data.w1  <- filter(share.data.w1, !is.na(cciw_w1))


#dropping the participants from Israel
share.data.w1  <- filter(share.data.w1, !is.na(age_int))

#dropping unused levels
share.data.w1 <- droplevels(share.data.w1)
# assign weights equal to 1 to all participants in an additional variable to obtain unweighted estimates
share.data.w1$wAll1 <- 1


# setting to missing the strata and psu values that are empty
share.data.w1$stratum1[share.data.w1$stratum1==""] <- NA
share.data.w1$psu[share.data.w1$psu==""] <- NA
# number of missing psu
num.na.psu <- sum(is.na(share.data.w1$psu))
share.data.w1$psu <- as.numeric(share.data.w1$psu)

# using constant values for strata within country, all different values of psu for countries that did not have them in the design
share.data.w1$stratum1[is.na(share.data.w1$stratum1)] <- paste(share.data.w1$country[is.na(share.data.w1$stratum1)], "fake stratum")
share.data.w1$psu[is.na(share.data.w1$psu)] <- c((10^9+1) :  (10^9+num.na.psu)) 


# specify the sampling design
dstrat <- survey::svydesign(id=~psu,strata=~stratum1, weights=~ cciw_w1,
data = share.data.w1, nest=TRUE)

# stratum1 is a factor variable for stratum used for sampling, usually geographical units

my.mod <- glm(eurodcat_imp ~ rcs(age_int_stand) + gender + region + 
                       rcs(age_int_stand):region + rcs(age_int_stand):gender + gender:region ,  
                                             data=share.data.w1.sens, family="binomial",  x=TRUE, y=TRUE)

#save the spline terms in the complete data set for further use

                                                                    age2 = my.mod$x[,3],
                                                                    age3 = my.mod$x[,4],
                                                                    age4 = my.mod$x[,5])

Knots <- Hmisc::rcspline.eval(x = share.data.w1$age_int_stand, nk = 5, knots.only = TRUE)

#reproduces the spline values for age, expands for each integer value from 50 to 90
age = rcspline.eval(c(50:90)-50, knots=Knots)
age <- cbind.data.frame(age1=c(50:90)-50, age )
dimnames(age)[[2]] <- c("age1", "age2", "age3", "age4")

The estimated OR for the risk factors with weighted and unweighted analyses were mostly similar, the weighted analysis had larger variability in the estimates.

Omitting the participants with large weights led to results that were very comparable with weighted and unweighted analyses, and there is no important difference in the conclusions that would be drawn from the two analyses. It is suggested that when a few influential observations happen to have large sampling weights, as in our case, neither the weighted nor the unweighted analysis is entirely reliable.

Similar results were obtained removing a smaller number of influential observations (77 observations with weight above 25000, data not shown).

Also in the adjusted analysis the variability was greatly reduced by removing the participants with large weights. The estimated OR for the risk factors with weighted and unweighted analyses were mostly similar, the weighted analysis had larger variability in the estimates.

Omitting the participants with large weights led to results that were very comparable with weighted and unweighted analyses, and there is no important difference in the conclusions that would be drawn from the two analyses, with the exeption of the results that refer to the Eastern region, where the probabilities estimated by the weighted model were larger, even after adjusting for the risk factors.

Similar results were obtained removing a smaller number of influential observations (0 observations with weight above 25000, data not shown).

1.3 Analysis of first interviews

For the analysis of first interviews, where we combine the data from different waves, the study weights have to be scaled so that they would add up to the population total in each wave. The distribution of first interviews across waves is quite heterogeneous, as it can be seen in the table below.

An additional problem is that only a subset of participants have their first interview in a certain wave (this subset is usually younger compared to the participants that were included previously), and their cross-sectional weights should be rescaled, taking the composition of the sample into account. As the number of first interviews in some waves and countries is very small, we expect that in these instances the rescaling might produce very large and very imprecise weights.

# retrieval of weights for all waves 
share.data.weights.all <- f_readRShare(
  datadir = "sharedata",
  waves = c(1,2,4,5,6),
  modules = c("gv_weights", "cv_r"),
  modules.wX = NULL  ,
  countries = NULL,
  variables.in.modules = list(gv_weights = NULL, cv_r = c("age_int", "gender", "yrbirth")),
  keep.module.name.in.vars = FALSE,
  verbose = FALSE
)$df.w


SD.joined <- left_join(share.data.first.interview, share.data.weights.all, by=c("mergeid", "Wave"))

SD.joined <- mutate(SD.joined, 
              cciw= case_when(
         Wave=="Wave 1" ~ cciw_w1,
         Wave=="Wave 2" ~ cciw_w2,
         Wave=="Wave 4" ~ cciw_w4,
         Wave=="Wave 5" ~ cciw_w5,
         Wave=="Wave 6" ~ cciw_w6
         
            ))


country.levels <- levels(SD.joined$country.x)

for (my.country in country.levels) {
      # filter the country specific data
      tmpG <- filter(SD.joined , country.x == my.country)
      
      
       m <- tmpG %>% group_by(categoryAgeGenderW, .drop=FALSE)  %>% select(starts_with("cciw_w")) %>% summarise_all(sum, na.rm=TRUE) %>% as.data.frame()
               m <- m[1:num.levels,]
               m$sumcc<- apply(m[,-1], 1, sum)
      
}
